english:
  title: At Chokseok Pavilion in Jinju
  author: Baek Mi-gyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    What matter if fortune has not yet favored me?
    The lake and mountains call for verses to be sung.
    Whose keen eye first envisioned this dwelling place?
    I boast that my years have not yet brought decay.

    Leaning on the pillar, heaven and earth seem joined as one,
    Where rippling waters weave through curtains hung mid-air.
    The autumn moon stirs that ethereal grace
    Which moved the Banished Immortal to compose,
    As twilight songs drift from fishermen below.

    Over wine and idle talk I ease my restless heart—
    Even four days apart seem all too long to bear.
    On the southwestern shore, where dense groves sway,
    I fear my humble pavilion shines too bright,
    And wonder if such beauty brings its own reproach.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Banished Immortal' (李白/Li Bai) was renowned for his poetic celebrations of natural beauty and wine.
    - The fishermen's evening songs reference a famous poem about the Yangtze River at dusk, evoking themes of simple contentment and natural harmony.
